@kevinz Had the exact same thing with Redis. One shard was getting hammered while others were idle.

Dependabot bumped uuid to 9.0.2 and suddenly perfect shard distribution. Rolled back to verify - hotspot returns immediately. Bump to 9.0.2 again - perfect distribution.

How can a UUID library affect Redis sharding?

@tmiller Confirmed. Built a custom analyzer - there's subtle structure in the bit patterns.

But here's the weird part: standard randomness tests can't see it. You only notice when you use the UUIDs in real systems - hash tables, distributed locks, cache keys.

It's like they're optimized for how we actually use them.

@alexm-sf I tried your XOR test. You're right, there's something there.

It's not noise. There are repeating patterns every 128 bits. But only when XORing sequential UUIDs, not random pairs.

How does it know they're sequential?
